Train XOR neural network¶

In [ ]:
def calculate_error(y_hat, y): # 1 - accuracy
    return 1 - np.mean((torch.argmax(y_hat, dim=1, keepdim=True) - torch.argmax(y, dim=1, keepdim=True) == 0).numpy())
In [ ]:
xor_net = torch.nn.Sequential(
    torch.nn.Linear(2, 3),
    torch.nn.ReLU(),
    torch.nn.Linear(3,2),
    torch.nn.Softmax()
)

def init_weights(m):
    torch.manual_seed(123)
    if isinstance(m, torch.nn.Linear):
        torch.nn.init.normal_(m.weight, std=1)

xor_net.apply(init_weights)

learning_rate = 0.1
loss = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(reduction='none')
optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(xor_net.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
In [ ]:
losses = []
errors_train = []
errors_test = []
num_iter = 100


for epoch in range(num_iter):
    losses_iter = []
    errors_train_iter = []
    errors_test_iter = []
    
    for X, y in xor_dataloader_test:
        y_hat = xor_net(X)
        errors_test_iter += [calculate_error(y_hat, y)]


    for X, y in xor_dataloader_train:
        y_hat = xor_net(X)
        l = loss(y_hat, y)
        errors_train_iter +=  [calculate_error(y_hat, y)]
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        l.mean().backward()
        losses_iter += [l.mean().item()]
        optimizer.step()
   
    errors_train += [np.mean(errors_train_iter)]
    errors_test += [np.mean(errors_test_iter)]
    losses += [np.mean(losses_iter)]

In [ ]:
def init_weights(m, std=1):
    if isinstance(m, torch.nn.Linear):
        torch.nn.init.normal_(m.weight, std=1)

def train_nn(nnet, dataloader_test, dataloader_train, lr=0.1, n_epochs = 40, init_std=1):
    torch.manual_seed(0)
    nnet.apply(lambda x: init_weights(x, init_std))
    loss = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(reduction='none')
    optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(nnet.parameters(), lr=lr)
    
    losses = []
    errors_train = []
    errors_test = []

    for epoch in range(n_epochs):
        losses_iter = []
        errors_train_iter = []
        errors_test_iter = []
        
        for X, y in dataloader_test:
            y_hat = nnet(X)
            errors_test_iter += [calculate_error(y_hat, y)]


        for X, y in dataloader_train:
            y_hat = nnet(X)
            l = loss(y_hat, y)
            errors_train_iter +=  [calculate_error(y_hat, y)]
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            l.mean().backward()
            losses_iter += [l.mean().item()]
            optimizer.step()
    
        errors_train += [np.mean(errors_train_iter)]
        errors_test += [np.mean(errors_test_iter)]
        losses += [np.mean(losses_iter)]
    return {'nnet':nnet, 'e_train':errors_train, 'e_test':errors_test, 'loss':losses}

  • We can see that every architecture has a decreasing loss.
  • The best fitted is the simplest network (with 3 neurons).
  • Test errors are more rugged, but even larger networks seem not to be overfitting. This may be a result of uniformly distributed artificial data.
  • Larger nets must have fallen into local minimum.

Learning rate comparison¶

In [ ]:
def reset_net(net):
    torch.manual_seed(0)
    net.apply(init_weights)

def train_net_lr(net, learning_rate):
    loss = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(reduction='none')
    optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(net.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
    losses = []
    errors_train = []
    errors_test = []
    num_iter = 100


    for epoch in range(num_iter):
        losses_iter = []
        errors_train_iter = []
        errors_test_iter = []
        
        for X, y in xor_dataloader_test:
            y_hat = net(X)
            errors_test_iter += [calculate_error(y_hat, y)]


        for X, y in xor_dataloader_train:
            y_hat = net(X)
            l = loss(y_hat, y)
            errors_train_iter +=  [calculate_error(y_hat, y)]
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            l.mean().backward()
            losses_iter += [l.mean().item()]
            optimizer.step()
    
        errors_train += [np.mean(errors_train_iter)]
        errors_test += [np.mean(errors_test_iter)]
        losses += [np.mean(losses_iter)]
        
    return {'lr':learning_rate, 'loss':losses, 'es_test':errors_test, 'es_train':errors_train}

# First set up the figure, the axis, and the plot element we want to animate
fig = plt.figure()
x = np.linspace(-10, 10, 21)
y = np.linspace(-10, 10, 21)
g = np.meshgrid(x, y, indexing='xy')
mesh = torch.tensor([(x,y) for x, y in zip(*(x.flat for x in g))], dtype=torch.float)
# reset NN
xor_net.apply(init_weights)

out = xor_net(X)
plt.contourf(x, y, out[:,1].detach().numpy().reshape(21,21))

# initialization function: plot the background of each frame
def init():
    plt.contourf(x, y, np.zeros(shape=(21,21)))

# animation function.  This is called sequentially
def animate(i):
    out = xor_net(mesh)
    for X, y_ in xor_dataloader_train:
        y_hat = xor_net(X)
        l = loss(y_hat, y_)
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        l.mean().backward()
        optimizer.step()
    plt.contourf(x, y, out[:,1].detach().numpy().reshape(21,21))

anim = animation.FuncAnimation(fig, animate, init_func=init,
                               frames=200, interval=20, blit=False)

# save the animation as an mp4.  This requires ffmpeg or mencoder to be
# installed.  The extra_args ensure that the x264 codec is used, so that
# the video can be embedded in html5.  You may need to adjust this for
# your system: for more information, see
# http://matplotlib.sourceforge.net/api/animation_api.html
anim.save('basic_animation.mp4', fps=30, extra_args=['-vcodec', 'libx264'])

plt.show()
